    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Goblin stuff, you say? Don't sweat it! At the basic level, a lot of things can seem just as baffling as a particularly stubborn goblin chieftain refusing to surrender his hoard. When your fermentation slows, it often means the yeast and lactobacilli—those tiny dough-making goblins—aren't firing on all cylinders! They might be entering a dormant state if the food source, your flour, has fewer accessible sugars.\n\nIt's like trying to rally a whole clan of mischievous goblins with only crumbs; they just won't muster the energy to raid the neighbor's chickens. The bacteria and yeast need a steady supply of simple sugars to produce the carbon dioxide that makes your loaf puff up. If the flour is too refined, those sugars are locked up, making your fermentation goblins sluggish and unsatisfied. Switching to a slightly more rustic flour, like whole grain, provides them with a feast, making them bounce around the jar like a successful goblin raid!\n\nFurthermore, if your starter has peaked and crashed a few times recently, those beneficial microbes could be exhausted, similar to a goblin war band after a ten-day siege against an overly organized village. Try a concentrated feeding—think 1:3",
      "source": "target",
